<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Foreign_players">Foreign players</span></h3>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="International_influence_2">International influence</span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/List_of_foreign_NBA_players" title="List of foreign NBA players">List of foreign NBA players</a></div>
<p>Following pioneers like <a href="/wiki/Vlade_Divac" title="Vlade Divac">Vlade Divac</a> (<a href="/wiki/Serbia" title="Serbia">Serbia</a>) and <a href="/wiki/Dra%C5%BEen_Petrovi%C4%87" title="Dražen Petrović">Dražen Petrović</a> (<a href="/wiki/Croatia" title="Croatia">Croatia</a>) who joined the NBA in the late 1980s, an increasing number of international players have moved directly from playing elsewhere in the world to starring in the NBA. Below is a short list of foreign players who have won NBA awards or have been otherwise recognized for their contributions to basketball, either currently or formerly active in the league:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/%C5%A0ar%C5%ABnas_Mar%C4%8Diulionis" title="Šarūnas Marčiulionis">Šarūnas Marčiulionis</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lithuania" title="Lithuania">Lithuania</a> – 2014 inductee into the <a href="/wiki/Naismith_Memorial_Basketball_Hall_of_Fame" title="Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame">Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame</a>. First Soviet Union and one of the very first Europeans to sign contract with NBA club and to play solidly in the league, helping to lead the way for the internationalization of the league in the late 1990s.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Toni_Kuko%C4%8D" title="Toni Kukoč">Toni Kukoč</a>, <a href="/wiki/Croatia" title="Croatia">Croatia</a> – 3-time NBA Champion with Chicago Bulls (1996, 1997, 1998), named in 2008 as one of the <a href="/wiki/50_Greatest_EuroLeague_Contributors" class="mw-redirect" title="50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors">50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Vlade_Divac" title="Vlade Divac">Vlade Divac</a>, <a href="/wiki/Serbia" title="Serbia">Serbia</a> – 2-time Olympic silver medalist, 2001 NBA All-Star, 2-time World Champion, 3-time European Champion, 50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Arvydas_Sabonis" title="Arvydas Sabonis">Arvydas Sabonis</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lithuania" title="Lithuania">Lithuania</a>&#160;– 2011 inductee into the <a href="/wiki/Naismith_Memorial_Basketball_Hall_of_Fame" title="Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame">Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame</a>, 1984, 1985, 1988, 1995, 1999 Euroscar Player of the Year, 1985, 1997 Mr. Europa Player of the Year, Olympic gold medalist in <a href="/wiki/Basketball_at_the_1988_Summer_Olympics" title="Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics">1988</a> with the <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union_national_basketball_team" title="Soviet Union national basketball team">Soviet Union</a> and bronze medalist in <a href="/wiki/Basketball_at_the_1992_Summer_Olympics" title="Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics">1992</a> and <a href="/wiki/Basketball_at_the_1996_Summer_Olympics" title="Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics">1996</a> with <a href="/wiki/Lithuania_men%27s_national_basketball_team" title="Lithuania men's national basketball team">Lithuania</a>, 1996 NBA All-Rookie First Team, 50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dirk_Nowitzki" title="Dirk Nowitzki">Dirk Nowitzki</a>, Germany&#160;– NBA Champion with Dallas Mavericks (2011), MVP of the <a href="/wiki/2002_FIBA_World_Championship" title="2002 FIBA World Championship">2002 FIBA World Championship</a> and <a href="/wiki/EuroBasket_2005" title="EuroBasket 2005">EuroBasket 2005</a>, member of the all-tournament team in the <a href="/wiki/2002_FIBA_World_Championship" title="2002 FIBA World Championship">2002 FIBA World Championship</a>, 2002–2006 and 2011 <a href="/wiki/Euroscar" title="Euroscar">Euroscar</a> winner, 2005 <a href="/wiki/Mr._Europa" title="Mr. Europa">Mr. Europa</a>, 2005 and 2011 <a href="/wiki/FIBA_Europe_Player_of_the_Year" class="mw-redirect" title="FIBA Europe Player of the Year">FIBA Europe Player of the Year</a>, <a href="/wiki/2006%E2%80%9307_NBA_season" title="2006–07 NBA season">2007</a> <a href="/wiki/National_Basketball_Association_Most_Valuable_Player_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="National Basketball Association Most Valuable Player Award">NBA MVP</a>, 2011 <a href="/wiki/Bill_Russell_NBA_Finals_Most_Valuable_Player_Award" title="Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award">Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award</a>, 2006 <a href="/wiki/NBA_Three-Point_Shootout_champion" class="mw-redirect" title="NBA Three-Point Shootout champion">NBA Three-Point Shootout champion</a> and 11-time NBA All-Star (entered the NBA in 1998)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hedo_T%C3%BCrko%C4%9Flu" title="Hedo Türkoğlu">Hedo Türkoğlu</a>, Turkey&#160;– 2008 <a href="/wiki/NBA_Most_Improved_Player_Award" title="NBA Most Improved Player Award">Most Improved Player Award</a> winner, member of the all-tournament team in the <a href="/wiki/2010_FIBA_World_Championship" title="2010 FIBA World Championship">2010 FIBA World Championship</a> (entered the NBA in 2000)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pau_Gasol" title="Pau Gasol">Pau Gasol</a>, Spain&#160;– 2-time NBA Champion with Los Angeles Lakers (2009 &amp; 2010), Three time <a href="/wiki/NBA_All-Star" class="mw-redirect" title="NBA All-Star">NBA All-Star</a>, 2002 <a href="/wiki/NBA_Rookie_of_the_Year_Award" title="NBA Rookie of the Year Award">NBA Rookie of the Year</a>, 2004 and 2009 Mr. Europa, <a href="/wiki/2006_FIBA_World_Championship" title="2006 FIBA World Championship">2006 FIBA World Championship</a> MVP, 2008 and 2009 <a href="/wiki/Euroscar_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Euroscar Award">Euroscar</a> and <a href="/wiki/FIBA_Europe_Player_of_the_Year_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="FIBA Europe Player of the Year Award">FIBA Europe Player of the Year</a>, <a href="/wiki/EuroBasket_2009" title="EuroBasket 2009">EuroBasket 2009</a> MVP, winner of the <a href="/wiki/J._Walter_Kennedy_Citizenship_Award" title="J. Walter Kennedy Citizenship Award">NBA Citizenship Award</a> in 2012 (entered the NBA in 2001)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Andrei_Kirilenko" title="Andrei Kirilenko">Andrei Kirilenko</a>, Russia&#160;– <a href="/wiki/EuroBasket_2007" title="EuroBasket 2007">EuroBasket 2007</a> MVP, 2007 FIBA Europe Player of the Year (drafted in 1999, played in the NBA from 2001 to 2011 before returning to Russia due to the lockout, returned in 2012 as a member of the Minnesota Timberwolves.)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tony_Parker" title="Tony Parker">Tony Parker</a>, France&#160;– 4-time NBA Champion with the Spurs, <a href="/wiki/2007_NBA_Finals" title="2007 NBA Finals">2007 NBA Finals</a> MVP and 2007 Euroscar winner (entered the NBA in 2001)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Manu_Gin%C3%B3bili" title="Manu Ginóbili">Manu Ginóbili</a>, <a href="/wiki/Argentina" title="Argentina">Argentina</a>&#160;– 4-time NBA Champion with San Antonio Spurs, 2008 <a href="/wiki/NBA_Sixth_Man_of_the_Year_Award" title="NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award">Sixth Man Award</a> winner, 50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors, gold medal in the <a href="/wiki/Basketball_at_the_2004_Summer_Olympics_%E2%80%93_Men%27s_tournament" title="Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament">2004 Summer Olympics</a> with <a href="/wiki/Argentine_national_basketball_team" class="mw-redirect" title="Argentine national basketball team">Argentina</a> (drafted in 1999, entered the NBA in 2002)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Yao_Ming" title="Yao Ming">Yao Ming</a>, China&#160;– First pick in the <a href="/wiki/2002_NBA_draft" title="2002 NBA draft">2002 NBA draft</a> and 7-time NBA All-Star (played in the NBA from 2002 to 2011)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Leandro_Barbosa" title="Leandro Barbosa">Leandro Barbosa</a>, Brazil&#160;– NBA Champion with Golden State Warriors (2015),<sup id="cite_ref-barbosachamp_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-barbosachamp-61">[61]</a></sup> 2007 <a href="/wiki/NBA_Sixth_Man_of_the_Year_Award" title="NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award">Sixth Man Award</a> winner (entered the NBA in 2003)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Andrea_Bargnani" title="Andrea Bargnani">Andrea Bargnani</a>, Italy&#160;– <a href="/wiki/List_of_first_overall_NBA_draft_picks" title="List of first overall NBA draft picks">First pick</a> in the <a href="/wiki/2006_NBA_draft" title="2006 NBA draft">2006 NBA draft</a> by the <a href="/wiki/Toronto_Raptors" title="Toronto Raptors">Toronto Raptors</a> (entered the NBA in 2006)</li>
</ul>
<p>On some occasions, young players, most but not all from the English-speaking world, have attended U.S. colleges before playing in the NBA. Notable examples are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Nigerian <a href="/wiki/Hakeem_Olajuwon" title="Hakeem Olajuwon">Hakeem Olajuwon</a> (<a href="/wiki/1984_NBA_draft" title="1984 NBA draft">top draft pick in 1984</a>, 2-time champion, 12-time All-Star, 1994 MVP, 1994 and 1995 Finals MVP, 1994 and 1995 Defensive Player of the Year, only player to receive the MVP Award, Defensive Player of the Year Award, and Finals MVP award in the same season, and Hall of Famer)</li>
<li>Congolese <a href="/wiki/Dikembe_Mutombo" title="Dikembe Mutombo">Dikembe Mutombo</a> (Four time <a href="/wiki/NBA_Defensive_Player_of_the_Year_Award" title="NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award">NBA Defensive Player of the Year</a>, selected fourth overall by the Denver Nuggets in the 1991 NBA Draft and 8-time NBA All-Star)</li>
<li>Dutchman <a href="/wiki/Rik_Smits" title="Rik Smits">Rik Smits</a> (1988 second overall pick, 1998 NBA All-Star, played 12 years for the Indiana Pacers)</li>
<li>German <a href="/wiki/Detlef_Schrempf" title="Detlef Schrempf">Detlef Schrempf</a> (Sixth Man Award winner in 1991 and 1992, 3-time All-Star)</li>
<li>Canadian <a href="/wiki/Steve_Nash" title="Steve Nash">Steve Nash</a> (2005 and 2006 MVP)</li>
<li>Australians <a href="/wiki/Luc_Longley" title="Luc Longley">Luc Longley</a> (3-time champion with the Bulls in the 1990s) and <a href="/wiki/Andrew_Bogut" title="Andrew Bogut">Andrew Bogut</a>, (<a href="/wiki/2005_NBA_draft" title="2005 NBA draft">top draft pick in 2005</a>).</li>
<li>Sudanese-born Englishman <a href="/wiki/Luol_Deng" title="Luol Deng">Luol Deng</a> (2007 winner of the <a href="/wiki/NBA_Sportsmanship_Award" title="NBA Sportsmanship Award">NBA Sportsmanship Award</a>)</li>
</ul>
<p>Since 2006, the NBA has faced <a href="/wiki/EuroLeague" title="EuroLeague">EuroLeague</a> teams <a href="/wiki/EuroLeague_vs._NBA_games" class="mw-redirect" title="EuroLeague vs. NBA games">in exhibition matches</a> in the <a href="/wiki/NBA_Europe_Live_Tour" class="mw-redirect" title="NBA Europe Live Tour">NBA Europe Live Tour</a>, and since 2009 in the <a href="/wiki/EuroLeague_American_Tour" title="EuroLeague American Tour">EuroLeague American Tour</a>.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/2013%E2%80%9314_NBA_season" title="2013–14 NBA season">2013–14 season</a> opened with a record 92 international players on the opening night rosters, representing 39 countries and comprising over 20% of the league<sup id="cite_ref-auto_24-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-24">[24]</a></sup> The NBA defines "international" players as those born outside the 50 United States and Washington, D.C. This means that:</p>
<ul>
<li>Players born in U.S. possessions such as <a href="/wiki/Puerto_Rico" title="Puerto Rico">Puerto Rico</a> and the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Virgin_Islands" title="United States Virgin Islands">U.S., Virgin Islands</a>, most notably USVI native <a href="/wiki/Tim_Duncan" title="Tim Duncan">Tim Duncan</a>, are counted as "international" even though they are U.S. citizens by birth, and may even have represented the U.S. in international competition (like Duncan).</li>
<li>U.S.-born players are not counted as "international" even if they were born with citizenship in another country and represent that country internationally, such as <a href="/wiki/Joakim_Noah" title="Joakim Noah">Joakim Noah</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Kosta_Koufos" title="Kosta Koufos">Kosta Koufos</a>.</li>
</ul>
